Roulette by Chelsea birch<br>
<br>
<br>
Max strode casually up to the Roulette table.  He placed his bets on: Black, Even and 8 Or 11.  A $300 bet total.  The dealer passed his hand over the table and declared, “No more bets.”  The dealer spun the wheel a few times, and dropped the little white ball into the ring.  The spinning slowed and the ball dropped into the black “8” pocket.  The dealer handed Max $2100 in chips.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Max Doyle pocketed his chips and walked over to a couch.  He sat down and hailed a waitress over.  He asked her for a drink, took one, and watched her walk away.  He laughed to himself.  Maybe he’d go find some of his gambling friends and tell them an amusing story about himself that never really happened.  That’s the way it was in the High-Roller rooms of the Ivory Tiger Casino.   No one actually knew anything about each other, except for names, which were very probably made up too.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Max found the man who called himself Roland, and handed him a $25 chip. Roland tossed him back one of the same.  It was one of those things; Roland wouldn’t talk to you before you exchanged chips with him. “Roland.  How are you, my friend?” Max asked.  Roland inclined his head towards Max to signal that he was fine.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Roland could talk; Max had heard him a few times.  He had a deep, sonorous voice, which made everyone in the casino wonder how he was important in the world.  Roland was important in the world, he was the owner of a large “dotcom” company, and lived alone in a mansion somewhere in the countryside according to rumour.  Roland never acknowledged or denied the rumors; he didn’t seem to care what anyone thought about him.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp There were two other people who Max was involved with in the casino.  Silver, who was Roland’s significant other, but a lot of people said that the only reason that she was involved with him was because he was the High Roller of the casino.  Silver was tall, blonde, and absolutely gorgeous.  The other person Max knew slowly weaved her way to the tables towards them.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lucille Severanti was average height, had long, straight brown hair with red highlights, and deep, emerald green eyes.  Max thought that no one ever called her by her real name; she was introduced to everyone as “Lucky Seven”.  Max had asked Lucky to marry him about nine times now.  She had refused him each time, but saying that she would one day when he had enough money to have them live a lush life somewhere in the suburbs of Beverly Hills. <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Lucky Seven joined Roland and Max, and tossed Roland a $10 chip.  He returned one of the same and greeted her with a wave.  Lucky stared at Max until he was very self-conscious, then said, “Well, how much did you win tonight?”  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Max paused.  “I’m not done yet.” He finally answered, “But $1900 profit so far, one bet.”  Lucky beamed at him.<br>
  “You are amazing.” She whispered, and then signaled Silver over to join them.<br>
Silver walked over and joined them.  She flipped Roland a $100 chip and let the one he tossed back to her fall onto the floor.  Roland greeted her with a booming, “Good Evening, Silver!” as if he hadn’t seen her in five years, even though they most probably came to the casino together.  Max stared at Silver.  Even with Lucky right there, he couldn’t help but be totally stunned by her.  <br>
Lucky and Silver went off somewhere to find a place to play slots, and Max drained his drink and walked towards the back of the casino to the Roulette tables.  He signaled the dealer that he should come talk to him when he had his break.  The dealer quickly closed the bets and came over to Max.<br>
“Whatcha wanting, Max?’ the dealer asked.<br>
“I want to boost the odds for me, Murdoc.” Max replied.<br>
Max explained his plan to Murdoc, the dealer, detailing exactly how to loosen the pockets on the roulette wheel, and where to drill the holes in the rim.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I dunno ‘bout this, Max.” Murdoc said. “Whatcha gonna do if I get busted? Are you gonna take the rap? I can’t, man, I’ll lose my job.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “If you lose your job then I’ll get you a new one, in a new casino.  It’ll be okay, you know where they won’t be able to see you, then after that, how are they gonna know you’re the one tampering with the wheel?”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “They ain’t, but you gonna get me a new wheel? Mine’ll be messed.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “I’m not getting you a new wheel, you can buy your own with your half of the money.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Yeah, I better get half, man.  Nothing betta change, Max, I’ll kill you dead. DEAD, man!” Murdoc exclaimed. “I’m not joking.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Max walked away without answering, there was no talking to Murdoc when he got angry and crazy.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The plan was this:  <br>
1.&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Tamper with the Roulette wheel.<br>
2.&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Place large bets and win six million dollars<br>
3.&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Divide the money 50 / 50 <br>
4.&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Take his half and split to Beverly Hills with Lucky<br>
<br>
Of course, that wasn’t going to happen.  They were going to win the six million and everything, but then Max was just planning of skipping town, and having the whole six mill’ to himself.<br>
