<br>
<br>
The next evening, Max put on his black-tie gambling clothes, and left a note for Lucky that he was going to the casino and that she should meet him there later.  As he walked into the casino he thought to himself that he had better get a gun, if he was going to pull this thing off.  So he made arrangements with Roland, who just happened to deal guns on the side, to get a handgun from him.  Max chose a “Desert Eagle” a large, powerful gun.  He concealed it in the glove compartment in his car.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Max walked back into the casino and headed towards Murdoc’s Roulette table.  Murdoc signaled that he had done the work to the wheel, and Max placed his bets.  It seemed that lady luck was leaning in his direction.  Max got $2,000.  $5,000.  $10,000.  $1,000,000.  People were beginning to be suspicious.  Max took his chips, traded them in for cash, and had a drink with Roland and Silver.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp $3,000,000.  At $5,000,000, Lucky joined him.  He put his arm around her waist as he placed his last bets.  “We’re going to Beverly Hills, baby!!!”  The wheel spun.  $6,000,000.  Six Million dollars. He traded in his chips for cash.  Time seemed to slow down.  “C’mon Lucky Seven, we’re gone!”  They ran to his car.  He revved the engine and started to speed away when Murdoc came bursting out the doors.  <br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Murdoc grabbed the nearest car.  He slid into the driver’s seat of the ’67 Mustang Shelby GT 500 and slammed hard on the gas petal.  The two cars zoomed down the streets of Vegas and into the countryside.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Max pulled out onto a long, straight stretch of road.  He pulled his brand new, fully loaded Desert Eagle out of the glove compartment.  He told Lucky to take the wheel, and turned around and shot half a round at Murdoc.  Unfortunately, Max was a terrible shot.  He missed with the first two shots, and dinged the side of the car with the third, doing almost no damage.  He ducked and pushed Lucky out of the line of fire as three shots came flying back at him from the other car, one hitting his mirror, one his tire, and one his steering wheel.  The back left wheel deflated.  Another shot thudded into his front left wheel.<br>
The car started to tilt.  Murdoc Pulled up beside him and yelled, “I said that you were DEAD, man, I wasn’t joking, I was serious!!” Murdoc steered his car so that it scraped the right side of Max’s car.  Max lost control of the vehicle.  The car swerved off the road, and down an incline.  The car rolled, side-over-side-over-side.  Max held on for his life.  The car stopped rolling, stopped moving.  Time stopped.  Max flickered in and out of consciousness.   <br>
Murdoc towered over Max.  “I only wanted half, man, ain’t that hard. Shoulda done what you said you’d do. Sorry it had to end like this, I thought you were cool, man.”<br>
Murdoc grabbed the cash from Max’s shirt pocket and helped Lucky Seven out of the car.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Sorry Max,” she said. “But I’ve got to do what’s best for me, and I still really want to go to Beverly Hills.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp “Well, I can take you to Beverly Hills on my way to Mexico, Lucille.” Murdoc said.  “I’ll take you there and leave this lying jerk here.  I really am sorry, Man. Sorry.”<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Murdoc aimed the gun at Max.  Max stared down the barrel of a gun for the first, and last, time of his life.<br>
